    <name>
				<text>16.4.5.4 Differentiate to obtain power series</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>This exercise assumes knowledge of differentiation, this can be ignored if you have not seen differentiation before.<br><br>By differentiating the series for {@ser1@} find the power series for {@ser2@} and give a quadratic approximation. State its radius of convergence of the power series for {@ser2@}.</p>
<p>\({@ser2@} \approx\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt1]]<br></p>
<p>\(R = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">Using the known result from the binomial series \[(1+x)^p = 1 + px + \frac{p(p-1)}{2!}x^2 + \dots + \frac{p(p-1)(p-2)\cdots(p-n+1)}{n!}x^n \qquad |x|&lt;1,\] choose \(p={@po1@}\) and by differentiating obtain the power series expression for \({@ser2@}.\)</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">\[ {@ser1@} = {@taylor(ser1, x,0,3)@} \]</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">Differentiating both sides: \( \quad \displaystyle {@po1*ser2@} = {@diff(taylor(ser1, x,0,3), x)@}\)&nbsp;</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">Multiplying through by {@a1@}: \( \quad \displaystyle {@ser2@} = {@ta1@} \)</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">Using the sum notation, the binomial series is: \[(1+x)^p = \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \frac{p(p-1)(p-2)\cdots(p-n-1)}{n!}x^n\]</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">Here we have: \[b_p = \dfrac{p(p+1)\cdots(p-n+1)}{n!} \quad b_{p+1}=\dfrac{p(p-1)\cdots(p-n+1)(p-n)}{(n+1)!}\]</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">In this case, \[R= \lim_{p \to \infty}\left| \dfrac{b_p}{b_{p+1}}\right| =\lim_{p \to \infty} \left| \dfrac{p(p-1)\cdots(p-n+1)(p-n)}{(n+1)!} \dfrac{n!}{p(p+1)\cdots(p-n+1)}\right|= \]<br></p>
<p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">\[ \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{|p-n|}{n+1} = \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{\left| 1- \frac{p}{n}\right|}{1+\frac{1}{n}} =1\]</p><p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;">As we learned in the "Properties of power series" section, if \(P_1\) is a power series with radius of convergence \(R_1\) then \[ \dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}(P_1) \quad \mathrm{and} \quad \int(P_1)\mathrm{d}x\] are each power series with radius of convergence \(R_1.\)</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
